# Development Rules

When modifying this codebase, follow these rules strictly.

## Adding a New Command

1. Choose the right file in `commands/`:
   - `jira-read.mjs` — Read-only Jira queries
   - `jira-write.mjs` — Jira mutations (create, update, assign, transition)
   - `jira-sync.mjs` — Sprint sync and cache operations
   - `confluence-read.mjs` — Confluence queries

2. Add a command object to the exported array:
   ```javascript
   {
     name: 'command-name',
     async execute({ args, flags, client, config }) {
       // implementation
     },
   }
    It is automatically registered via commands/index.mjs.

    Add a help entry in lib/cli.mjs → HELP_TEXT.

    Add an intent mapping in .cursor/rules/02-commands-reference.mdc.

Rules for Command Implementations

    NEVER import from dotenv or read process.env directly. All config comes through the config parameter.
    NEVER hardcode Atlassian domains, project keys, or space keys. Read them from config.
    ALWAYS use client.requestJson() for API calls that return JSON. Use client.request() only for calls that return 204 No Content.
    ALWAYS call invalidateSprintCache(config) after write operations.
    Handle both flags.json (structured output) and text (formatted output).

Rules for API Modules (lib/jira/, lib/confluence/)

    These modules receive a client object, never raw credentials.
    They return data, they do NOT console.log.
    They throw ApiError on failure.
    One function per API operation. No god functions.

Rules for Formatters (lib/formatters/)

    Formatters receive data and return strings. They do NOT call APIs.
    Formatters do NOT console.log — they return the formatted string.
    Keep Jira-specific knowledge in lib/jira/transforms.mjs, not in formatters.

Rules for Configuration

    New required env vars: add to .env.example with a comment.
    New config fields: add to config.yaml with a comment, and handle the missing case with a sensible default in lib/config.mjs.
    New profiles: add an example (commented out) in config.yaml.

Testing

Run tests with npm test. When adding functionality:

    API modules: test with mocked HTTP responses
    Formatters: test with fixture data
    Config: test with sample YAML and env vars
